VALUES
(42, 11, 24, 18, 1, 7, 7, 'walketh through dry places', 'Spiritual Wanderings of Entities', 'Both passages emphasize the wandering nature of unclean spirits or Satan. The unclean spirit in Luke seeks rest in dry places, while Satan in Job describes his movement ''to and fro in the earth.''', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 24, 41, 5, 10, 10, 'unclean spirit', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence and desire of unclean spirits. In Luke, the spirit seeks rest after leaving, while in Mark, the spirits plead not to be sent away, indicating their desire to remain in a specific location.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 24, 23, 44, 3, 3, 'dry places', 'Connection of Dry Places and Thirst', 'This connection highlights the imagery of ''dry'' environments in both passages. In Luke, the unclean spirit seeks rest in ''dry places,'' while Isaiah speaks of pouring water on ''dry ground,'' suggesting a contrast between spiritual barrenness and divine provision.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 53, 2, 9, 12, 'swept and garnished', 'Connection of Deception and Preparation', 'This connection highlights the theme of deceptive appearances. In Luke 11:25, the house is ''swept and garnished,'' suggesting a false sense of security, while 2 Thessalonians 2:9-12 warns of strong delusion and belief in lies, indicating a similar deceptive state.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 61, 2, 10, 19, 'swept and garnished', 'Connection of Spiritual Condition', 'Both passages emphasize a state of being unclean or corrupted. Luke 11:25 mentions a space that is ''swept and garnished,'' suggesting a superficial cleanliness, while 2 Peter 2:10-19 describes individuals who are corrupt and indulge in fleshly desires, highlighting a deeper moral decay.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 65, 1, 8, 13, 'swept and garnished', 'Connection of Spiritual Condition', 'This connection highlights the state of being ''swept and garnished'' in Luke, which parallels the description of individuals in Jude as ''twice dead, plucked up by the roots.'' Both passages emphasize a superficial appearance of order or righteousness that conceals deeper corruption.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 19, 36, 3, 3, 'swept and garnished', 'Connection of Deceit and Preparation', 'This connection highlights the theme of superficiality in moral and spiritual states. In Luke, the house is ''swept and garnished,'' suggesting an outward appearance of cleanliness, while Psalms speaks of ''iniquity and deceit,'' indicating a lack of true wisdom and goodness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 19, 81, 11, 12, 'swept and garnished', 'Connection of Spiritual Condition', 'This connection highlights the state of being ''swept and garnished'' in Luke, which can be seen as a metaphor for the superficiality of Israel''s obedience in Psalms. Both passages emphasize a lack of true commitment to God, leading to abandonment to their own desires.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 40, 12, 44, 45, 'swept and garnished', 'Connection of Swept and Garnished', 'Both passages emphasize the state of being ''swept and garnished,'' indicating a preparation or emptiness that invites further danger. This connection highlights the theme of vulnerability to greater evil when one is not filled with righteousness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 25, 14, 24, 17, 22, NULL, 'Spiritual Condition and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize a state of being ''swept and garnished'' or spiritually prepared, yet ultimately forsaken due to disobedience. The neglect of true worship leads to dire consequences, as seen in the rejection of God''s prophets in 2 Chronicles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 43, 5, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Sin and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of returning to sin after healing. Luke warns that the last state can be worse, while John cautions against sinning again to avoid worse consequences.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 61, 2, 20, 22, 'the last state of that man is worse than the first', 'Worsening State After Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize that returning to a former state after experiencing salvation leads to a worse condition. The idea of being ''worse than the first'' in Luke parallels the notion in 2 Peter that it is ''better for them not to have known'' righteousness. This connection highlights the danger of falling back into sin.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 40, 12, 45, 45, 'seven other spirits more wicked than himself', 'Connection of Wicked Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the return of a spirit with seven others, resulting in a worse state. This connection highlights the theme of spiritual danger and deterioration.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 36, 1, 6, 6, 'last state of that man', 'Spiritual Reversion and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual regression. Both passages emphasize the danger of turning away from the Lord, leading to a worse state, as seen in the ''last state of that man'' and those ''turned back from the Lord.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 40, 23, 15, 15, 'worse than the first', 'Spiritual Deterioration and Hypocrisy', 'Both passages emphasize a worsening spiritual state. In Luke, the man becomes worse after being inhabited by more wicked spirits, while in Matthew, the proselyte becomes twofold more the child of hell, indicating a similar decline in spiritual condition.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 58, 6, 4, 8, 'last state of that man is worse than the first', 'Spiritual Decline and Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of spiritual regression. Luke 11:26 warns that a person''s last state can be worse than the first, while Hebrews 6:4-8 discusses the impossibility of renewal after falling away, indicating a severe consequence for rejecting enlightenment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 26, 58, 10, 26, 31, 'last state of that man is worse than the first', 'Consequences of Sin and Rejection', 'This connection highlights the consequences of sin and the danger of spiritual regression. Both passages emphasize that returning to a state of sin can lead to a worse outcome, as seen in the ''last state of that man is worse than the first'' and the warning of ''sorer punishment'' for those who reject grace.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 27, 42, 1, 42, 42, 'blessed is the womb that bare thee', 'Connection of Blessings in Luke', 'This connection highlights the theme of blessing associated with motherhood. Both passages emphasize the blessed status of the womb and the fruit of the womb.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 27, 42, 1, 48, 48, 'Blessed is the womb that bare thee', 'Blessed Mary and Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of being called blessed. Both passages emphasize the blessing associated with Mary, the mother of Jesus, and the acknowledgment of her role in bearing him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 27, 42, 23, 29, 29, 'the womb that bare thee', 'Blessings on Wombs and Barren', 'This connection highlights the contrasting views on motherhood and barrenness. Both passages emphasize the phrase ''the womb'' and the blessings associated with it, reflecting a shift in perception from one that celebrates motherhood to one that acknowledges the plight of the barren.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 27, 42, 1, 28, 28, 'Blessed is the womb that bare thee', 'Blessed Among Women', 'This connection highlights the theme of blessing attributed to women in relation to Jesus. Both passages emphasize the idea of being ''blessed'' in the context of motherhood and divine favor.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 42, 6, 47, 48, 'hear the word of God, and keep it', 'Hearing and Doing God''s Word', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing the word of God and acting upon it. Luke 11:28 highlights the blessing of those who keep God''s word, while Luke 6:47-48 illustrates the stability of those who do His sayings.', 'theme', 0.8109999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 42, 8, 21, 21, 'hear the word of God', 'Hearing and Doing God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the importance of both hearing and acting on the word of God. Both passages emphasize that true kinship with Jesus is defined by those who hear and keep or do the word of God.', 'theme', 0.713, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 19, 112, 1, 1, 'blessed are they that hear the word of God', 'Blessing through Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being blessed through obedience to God''s word and commandments. Luke highlights the importance of hearing and keeping God''s word, while Psalms focuses on delighting in His commandments.', 'theme', 0.685, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 59, 1, 21, 25, 'hear the word of God, and keep it', 'Connection of Hearing and Doing', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of not only hearing the word of God but also keeping it through action. Luke highlights the blessing of those who hear and keep God''s word, while James stresses the necessity of being doers of the word to avoid self-deception.', 'theme', 0.622, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 43, 13, 17, 17, 'blessed are they that hear the word of God, and keep it', 'Blessing in Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing and doing God''s word. Luke highlights the blessing of keeping God''s word, while John states happiness comes from doing what is known.', 'theme', 0.608, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 19, 1, 1, 3, 'blessed are they that hear the word of God, and keep it', 'Blessing through obedience to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of being blessed through adherence to God''s word. Both passages emphasize the importance of delighting in and keeping the law of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 28, 23, 48, 17, 18, 'hear the word of God, and keep it', 'Blessing of Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing and following God''s commands. Luke highlights the blessing of those who keep God''s word, while Isaiah expresses the peace that comes from hearkening to His commandments.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 29, 42, 11, 16, 16, NULL, 'Demand for Signs', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s desire for a sign. In Luke 11:16, they tempt Jesus by seeking a sign, while in Luke 11:29, Jesus responds to this demand by referring to the sign of Jonas.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 11, 29, 41, 8, 11, 12, NULL, 'Seeking Signs in Generations', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''this generation seek after a sign,'' highlighting a shared theme of skepticism among the people. They both convey a similar message regarding the refusal to accept faith without miraculous evidence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
